🚀 What is BOOT?

Boot means the process of starting a computer.

When you power ON a Linux system:

BIOS/UEFI starts hardware checks
Bootloader loads Linux kernel
Kernel starts the operating system
System services start
You get login screen

👉 This whole startup process is called booting

🧠 Simple meaning:

Boot = turning ON the system and starting Linux

⚙️ What is a DAEMON?

A daemon (pronounced “DEE-muhn”) is a background process that runs continuously in Linux.

It performs services without user interaction.

Examples:

web server
SSH service
logging service
cron jobs
📌 Example daemons:
systemd (manages all services)
sshd (remote login service)
httpd (web server)
🧠 Simple meaning:

Daemon = background service that keeps running and does work

🔥 Relationship between Boot and Daemon

When Linux boots:

👉 It automatically starts important daemons

Example:

At boot → system starts
Then systemd starts services like sshd, httpd, etc.
🍔 Easy analogy

Think of a restaurant:

Boot = Opening the restaurant
Daemons = Workers inside
chef cooks
waiter serves
cashier handles billing

All work in background while restaurant is open

⚡ Quick difference
Boot	Daemon
System startup process	Background service
Happens once at power ON	Runs continuously
Starts OS + services	Performs tasks
🎯 One-line summary
Boot = starting the system
Daemon = background service running after boot
